        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given a large integer represented as an integer array digits, where each digits[i] is the ith
                digit
                of the integer. The digits are ordered from most significant to least significant in left-to-right
                order.
                The large integer does not contain any leading 0's. Increment the large integer by one and return the
                resulting array of digits. The solution simulates manual addition by starting from the rightmost digit,
                adding 1, and propagating any carry to the left. If all digits were 9, we need to insert a new leading
                1.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: digits = [1,2,3] → Output: [1,2,4]. The number 123 + 1 = 124.
                Input: digits = [4,3,2,1] → Output: [4,3,2,2]. The number 4321 + 1 = 4322.
                Input: digits = [9,9,9] → Output: [1,0,0,0]. The number 999 + 1 = 1000, requiring a new leading digit.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    vector&lt;int&gt; plusOne(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; num) {
        // Start adding 1 from the last digit (like manual addition)
        for (int idx = num.size() - 1; idx &gt;= 0; idx--) {
            num[idx]++;                 // Add 1 to current digit
            if (num[idx] &lt; 10)          // No carry → we are done
                return num;
            num[idx] = 0;               // Carry generated, reset digit to 0
        }
        // If all digits were 9, add 1 at the front (e.g., 999 → 1000)
        num.insert(num.begin(), 1);
        return num;
    }
};</code></pre>
